It's hard to decide which routing is better and which is more useful as Ember.js and Rails style routing have two different functions. 

**Ember.js**
Your application has a set of states. The URL is just a reflection of the current state and not the state itself. The URL will just serialize into a readable application state that you can then act upon. I'd like to think of controllers like state handlers in this case. 

**Rails Style**
This is quite obvious as routing in this style is simply matching the URL directly. The URL becomes the current state and the application just reflects that!

Maybe we could give a flexible environment for routing on the client side to match both Rails-style (possibly default) and Ember.js style (more options). The ember.js style would be somewhat similar to it's default routing system but abstract the boilerplate stuff.

``` coffeescript
Tower.Route.draw ->

     @route 'index' ->
           @root '/'
           @controller 'application#index'

     @route 'posts.show' ->
           @root '/posts/:id'
           @controller 'posts#show'
```

Maybe even simplifying it:

``` coffeescript
Tower.Route.draw ->

    @route ->
        @root '/'
        @controller 'application#index'

```

Or even:

``` coffeescript
Tower.Route.draw ->

   @route '/', controller: 'application#index', ->
         @route '/:userId', controller: 'user#show', ->
```

Just some thoughts!

