One approach is to change this line:

``` javascript
Address = __extends(Address, _super);
```

to something like this:

``` javascript
Address = __extends('Address', _super);
```

That way it passes the string `'Address'` to `__extend`, and we can use that to set the class name. The way we're hooking into this is found here:

[packages/tower-support/shared/class.coffee#L8-12](https://github.com/viatropos/tower/blob/2376f81f1e37897f073db300a4d9d78b96a29572/packages/tower-support/shared/class.coffee#L8-12)

``` coffeescript
__extend: (child) ->
  object = Ember.Object.extend.apply @
  object.__name__ = child.name
  @extended.call(object) if @extended
  object
```

By passing a string instead of the result of `var Address` into that function, the `__extend` method above would just do this:

``` coffeescript
__extend: (name) ->
  object = Ember.Object.extend.apply @
  object.__name__ = name
  @extended.call(object) if @extended
  object
```

To make this change, we have to modify the [./coffee-inheritance.js](https://github.com/viatropos/tower/blob/master/coffee-inheritance.js) file so it passes a string, like above:

``` javascript
Address = __extends('Address', _super);
```

